    <section class="page-hero"><div class="wrap"><div class="crumb"><a href="index.html">Home</a> / Bats</div><h1>Bat work needs careful timing and documentation.</h1><p class="lead">Bats require a measured approach: identify likely access, understand seasonal limits, and avoid unsafe or improper exclusion.</p></div></section>
    <section class="section"><div class="wrap content"><div class="kicker">North Carolina-aware</div><h2>Inspection before action.</h2><p>Bat activity around vents, gables, roof returns, trim gaps, chimneys, or attic spaces should be evaluated carefully. The right plan depends on visible evidence, species behavior, timing, occupancy concerns, and applicable rules.</p><div class="steps"><div class="step"><div><strong>Locate likely entry points.</strong><br>We inspect accessible exterior and interior indicators such as staining, droppings, rub marks, sound reports, and structural gaps.</div></div><div class="step"><div><strong>Document timing and restrictions.</strong><br>Bat exclusion may be limited during sensitive seasonal periods and may require special handling depending on the situation.</div></div><div class="step"><div><strong>Plan correction work.</strong><br>Once appropriate, exclusion focuses on closing access points and reducing future re-entry risk.</div></div></div><div class="notice"><strong>Health note:</strong> If a bat is found in living space, especially where people were sleeping or direct contact may have occurred, contact local health authorities promptly for exposure guidance.</div></div></section>
